@graph.note: Early post-medieval is generally used for the 16th century and sometimes for the 17th century. The term 'middle post-medieval' is not used, and there is debate as to what constitutes the late post-medieval period. For the 18th century, it is best to stick simply to 'post-medieval' and qualify it using calendar dates.
@graph.label: Post-Medieval

@graph.note: The Old Stone Age defined by the practice of hunting and gathering and the use of chipped flint tools. This period is usually divided up into the Lower, Middle and Upper Palaeolithic.
@graph.label: Palaeolithic

@graph.note: The earliest subdivision of the Palaeolithic, or Old Stone Age; when the earliest use of flint tools appears in the current archaeological record. A hunter gatherer society is a defining characteristic.
@graph.label: Lower Palaeolithic

@graph.note: The second subdivision of the Paleolithic or Old Stone Age. Characterized by the fine flake tools of the Mousterian tradition and economically by a hunter gatherer society.
@graph.label: Middle Palaeolithic

@graph.note: The third and last subdivision of the Paleolithic or Old Stone Age; characterized by the development of projectile points made from bony materials and the development of fine blade flint tools.
@graph.label: Upper Palaeolithic

@graph.note: The Middle Stone Age, falling between the Palaeolithic and the Neolithic; marks the beginning of a move from a hunter gatherer society towards food producing society.
@graph.label: Mesolithic

@graph.note: The earliest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age.
@graph.label: Early Mesolithic

@graph.note: The latest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age.
@graph.label: Late Mesolithic

@graph.note: For monuments which are characteristic of the Paleolithic to Mesolithic but cannot be specifically assigned.
@graph.label: Early Prehistoric

@graph.note: The New Stone Age, this period follows on from the Palaeolithic and the Mesolithc and is itself suceeded by the Bronze Age. This period is characterized by the practice of a farming ecomony and extensive monumental constructions.
@graph.label: Neolithic

@graph.note: The earliest subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.
@graph.label: Early Neolithic

@graph.note: The second subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.
@graph.label: Middle Neolithic

@graph.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.
@graph.label: Late Neolithic

@graph.note: This period follows on from the Neolithic and is characterized by the increasing use of Bronzework. It is subdivided in the Early,Middle and Late Bronze Age.
@graph.label: Bronze Age

@graph.note: The earliest subdivision of the Bronze Age.
@graph.label: Early Bronze Age

@graph.note: The second subdivision of the Bronze Age.
@graph.label: Middle Bronze Age

@graph.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Bronze Age.
@graph.label: Late Bronze Age

@graph.note: This period follows on from the Bronze Age and is characterized by the use of iron for making tools and monuments such as hillforts and oppida. The Iron Age is taken to end with the Roman invasion.
@graph.label: Iron Age

@graph.note: The earliest subdivision of the Iron Age.
@graph.label: Early Iron Age

@graph.note: The second subdivision of the Iron Age.
@graph.label: Middle Iron Age

@graph.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Iron Age.
@graph.label: Late Iron Age

@graph.note: For monuments that can be identifed only to a date range from Neolithic to Iron Age.
@graph.label: Later Prehistoric

@graph.note: For monuments that can be identifed only to a date range from Palaeolithic to Iron Age.
@graph.label: Prehistoric

@graph.note: Traditionally begins with the Roman invasion in 43AD and ends with the emperor Honorius directing Britain to see to its own defence in 410AD.
@graph.label: Roman

@graph.note: This dates from the breakdown of Roman rule in Britain to the Norman invasion in 1066 and is to be used for monuments of post Roman, Saxon and Viking date.
@graph.label: Early Medieval

@graph.note: The Medieval period or Middle Ages begins with the Norman invasion and ends with the dissolution of the monasteries.
@graph.label: Medieval

@graph.note: Begins with the dissolution of the monasteries and ends with the death of Queen Victoria. Use more specific period where known.
@graph.label: Post Medieval
